text.tspan: 10.2.3COMMUNICATION ON OCCUPATIONAL HEALTH AND SAFETY ISSUESThe HSEQA Department will respond to any communication from external sources on matters concerning OH&S. This will includecommunication with contractors and other visitors to the workplace.All responsible persons within the organization are required to ensure participation and consultation of external workers by:appropriate involvement in hazard identification, risk assessment and determination of controls.Appropriate involvement in incident investigation.Involvement in the development and review of OHSAS policies and objectives.Representation on OHSAS matters.Consultation with contractors where there are changes that affect their own OHSAS.10.3COMMUNICATION WITH CUSTOMERSThe Company’s web site provides a transparent system for the ship owners, to avail of following information about their vessels usingthe dedicated password provided to them.The information available to owners at all times includes: a) Daily noon position message b) Vessel Performance report c) Main Engine performance d) Voyage summary e) Statement of Accounts (Summary of expenses incurred) f) Detailed crew list g) Certification status10.3.1COMMUNICATION WITH OWNERSFollowing are the general guidance on the regular and routine communications required with owners by the superintendents:A. Daily1) Read all e-mails including reports, arrival reports etc sent to owners/ charterers verify closely to ensure that none of vessels havemade any mistake. Errors should be brought to the notice of vessel and get them corrected. a) Confirm from the noon/ arrival messages whether vessel is meeting Charter Party speed and Diesel Oil consumptions.b) Owners’ messages shall be replied/ acknowledged promptly and within 30 minutes. It will be Fleet Manager/ HSEQASuperintendent’s responsibility to ensure that the owners’ queries are replied/ acknowledged within 30 minutes.B. Budgets Submissions and Periodical Reviews1) Budgets are to be submitted by the vessel’s technical superintendent to owners for approval 3 months before the end of thefinancial year through the General Manager, keeping in mind all the maintenance, up-gradation, New Regulations coming into force thefollowing year, mandatory inspections, trade of the vessel, etc. The budgets are to be prepared as realistic as possible.2) Budgets shall be reviewed on a yearly basis by the Technical Superintendent and discussed with the General Manager - Technical.All budgeted and non-budgeted items must be reflected in variance report with explanation for all non-budgeted items. At any time ifthe expense is over 5% of the budget an explanation by superintendent should be given with the variance report and sent to ownersby accounts Department.3) A close monitoring of the expenses by superintendent is essential. His proposed plans to minimize expenses and to bring back thebudgets in line with initial proposed budgets should be worked upon and if necessary a revised budget has to be proposed for thefollowing year / current year in consultation with the General Manager.4) Approvals from owners to be taken provided the “Over- Budgeted” category variance (averages) cannot be brought under controlwithin the following 3 Months.5) Generally if any cost is more than $10,000 for a single item; owner’s approval has to be sought. While ordering any item ofcost $10,000 and above, superintendent has to check with Accounting Department whether sufficient funds are available in theaccount. If insufficient funds are available then required supporting documents must be given to accounts department by thesuperintendent to make a Fund request to owners as necessary.6) In case the vessel requires upgradation, any major repairs or overhauls, which exceeds the current budget, then the superintendenthas to provide upgradation or repair plan with cost overview after getting it vetted by General Manager to take owner’s approvalbefore he can proceed with such an upgradation or repair.7) In consultation with Senior Management and after receiving their approvals, superintendent proposes, either as a revised Budget oras a Non Budgeted Header classified under upgradation of the vessel, to concerned owners to seek their written approvals.8) Typically a pre-delivery cost can be considered to be outside the Normal Operating Budget.10.4COMMUNICATION PROTOCOL
